    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="11"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d11">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72112/3527½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">20 April, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I agree with you that this form
                    is the best in which to announce our list of contraband and that we should make
                    an immediate announcement; but I am not clear as to the meaning of all of the
                    enclosed statement.<note n="14" xml:id="d11fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>No. 1 is clear. Under No. 2, is it your idea that all vehicles, of whatever kind,
                    should be considered contraband <hi rend="underline">no matter whither
                        bound</hi>? Under 3 I assume that the words “destined to come into the
                    possession or control of the enemy government or its officers or agents” is
                    meant to apply to “articles and materials for the manufacture thereof” as well
                    as to “all kinds of food and clothing”, but the language does not make that
                    clear. No. 4 is clear. Under 5 I assume that it is meant only to include
                    materials and metals useful in the manufacture of coin, currency, etc., but the
                    section might be read to include all metals of all kinds and uses. Of course
                    these points can all be made clear. They do not go to the merits.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
